sentences: Mark Karan (born January 13, 1955) is an American guitarist and singer.

He is best known for his long-term work with former members of the Grateful Dead, in RatDog (1998–2013), the Other Ones (1998–2000), Mickey Hart's band Planet Drum (1999), and Phil Lesh and Friends (2012).

He is best known for his long-term work with former members of the Grateful Dead, in RatDog (1998–2013), the Other Ones (1998–2000), Mickey Hart's band Planet Drum (1999), and Phil Lesh and Friends (2012).
In 2009 he released a solo album, Walk Through the Fire.
From 1986 to 1989 he was the guitarist and co-producer for the band Slings & Arrows which included Daniel Levitin on bass.
In 1998 he was selected, behind Steve Kimock, to fill Jerry Garcia's slot in The Other Ones, a band featuring former members of the Grateful Dead.
He played with the Other Ones on their 1998 and 2000 tours, and appeared with the 1998 lineup on their only album, the live compilation "The Strange Remain" in 1999.

A self-described 'non-deadhead' in 1998
On June 30, 2009, Karan released his debut album Walk Through the Fire to critical acclaim.
He has performed with a band called Live Dead '69 as part of the Airplane Family & Friends tour in December 2016.
In July 2007, Karan announced that he was being treated for throat cancer.
Karan returned to the lineup in March 2008 and remains in remission.

He has also played with Mickey Hart's Planet Drum and Phil Lesh & Friends over the years.
Karan was part of the RatDog lineup for most of the next 13 years.
His contributions to TV alone can currently be heard on over 15 networks and internationally in over 25 countries.
His TV appearances include Austin City Limits, VH1 Classic's All Star Jams, Late Night with Conan O'Brien, Late Late Night with Craig Kilborn, Today Show and Regis & Kathy Lee.
